\begin_layout Section
Bank corporate governance
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Laeven, Luc, 2013, Corporate Governance: What’s Special About Banks?, Annual
 Review of Financial Economics 5, 63–92.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Risk shifting problem 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The challenge of bank corporate governance is that they must balance the
 demands of being value-maximizing entities with serving the public interest
 (Mehran and Mooineaux, 2012; Mehran et al.
 2011).
 High leverage combined with subsidized deposit insurance, goverment guarantees
 and bank opacity creates motives and opportunities for risk-taking which
 can be optimal from the shareholders' point of view given limited liability,
 but not form an economy-wide point of view if such risk-taking increases
 the probability of failure that raises systemic risk.
 (Laeven, 2013, Adams and Mehran, 2003, 2011).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
how about bank non-executive compensation, options and bank risk? 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Financial reporting of banking industry
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Main topics:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(1) valuation and risk relevance of bank accounting informatiion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(2) the use of accounting discretion to manage earnings and reported regulatory
 capital
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(3) the effect of accounting on bank's economic behaviours before, during
 and after the financial crisis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(4) the role of fair value accounting
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a review see Beatty and Liao (2014), Bushman (2015) EPR, Ryan (2011)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Market players can obtain bank information from various sources: accounting
 information, information intermediaries like financial analysts, credit
 rating agencies, media, supervisory disclosures (stress test disclosure),
 bank voluntary disclosure, security prices.
 (Any study on each gourp of information sources' effect on bank?)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From the information receivers perspective, governement guarantee may dampen
 market participants incentive to gather and process information (Nier and
 Baumann, 2006; Furlong and Williams, 2006).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Theoy of transparency, reporting discretion in banking industry
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Positive side of bank transparency:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Market discipline:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
enhance corporate governance.
 (The complication of bank is that there is a confilict of interest between
 shareholders and other staker holders.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Enhance external monitoring of banks' risk-taking decision.
 (Rochet, 1992; Blume, 2002; Cordella and Yeyati, 1998).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Transparency can limit regulatory forbearance by providing a basis for market
 participants to extert pressure on bank supervisors to promptly intervene
 in troubled banks (Rochet, 2005).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Market discipline can also operate through regualtory intervention triggered
 by market signals, such as price movements of bank securities (Stephanou,
 2010; Flannery, 20010).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Transparency can reduce indiscriminate panic and rollover risk by reducing
 depositors' and other short term lenders' uncertainty about the solvency
 of individual banks (Ratnovski, 2013; Gortan and Huang, 2006).
 (Uncertainty lead to funding difficulty, which lead to bank liqudity crisis:
 Shin, 2009, Goldsmith-Pinkham and Yorumlmazer, 2010; Huang and Ratnovski,
 2011)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Transparency can reduce 
\series bold
financing friction
\series default
 on banks seeking to raise external capital in response to negative balance
 sheet shocks by reducing information asymmetry (Bushman and Williams, 2014;
 Beatty and Liao, 2011).
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Theories of monetary policy tranmission through bank lending channel (Kashyap
 and Stei, 1995, 2000)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Capita Crunch theory: regulatory capital concerns cause banks to restrict
 lending during economic downtrns (Bernanke and Lown, 1991; Bolton and Freixas,
 2006; Van den Heuvel, 2009).
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
Negative side of bank transparency
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It often asserted that banks are inherently opaque (Morgan, 2002; Flannery
 et al., 2004, 2013)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Transparency can lead to inefficient bank runs driven by coordination failures
 (Morris and Shin, 2002; Chen and Hasan, 2006)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Cause reputational contagion where disclosure of a bank's failure causes
 creditors in other banks to lose confidence in the bank regualtors' competence
 (Morrison and White, 2013)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Adversly affect incentives of bank managers and lead them to make inefficient
 investment decisions (Goldstein and Sapra, 2013)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
restrict inter-bank risk-sharing arrangements(Goldstein and Leitner, 2013)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Undermine banks' ability to produce private money (Gortan, 2013; 
\series bold
Dang et al., 2014
\series default
).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Dang et al.
 2014, opacity can help banks to provide risk sharing benefits, what does
 it mean? Secret keep of regulators (DeYoung et al.
 2001; Goldman and Sapra, 2013).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The relation between bank financial reporting and bank transparency is complicat
ed due ot accounting discretion.
 On the bright side, managers can use the discretion to 
\series bold
signial private information;
\series default
 on the dardside, it encourages 
\series bold
opportunistic behaviours
\series default
.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Banks' investment decisions are based on private information that is not
 availabel to those outside the bank (Diamond, 1984; Boyd and Prescott,
 1986).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Banks may also have incentives to suppress public information about their
 assets to support their role as liquidity providers (Gorton, 2013; Dang
 et al., 2014).
 This opaque lead to excessive-risk taking by individual banks and the contribut
ion of individual banks to the risk of the finnancial system (e.g., Fianncial
 Stability Forum, 2009, Brunnermeier et al., 2009; Hanson et al., 2011).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Bank balancesheet
\series default
 and economy (Gorton, 2013; Kashyap et al., 2002; Kashyap and Stein, 2000).
 To the extent that the balance sheets of many banks are simultaneously
 vulnerable to the same downside risk exposeures, negative economic shocks
 can cause banks to co-move and amplify shocks across the entire economy
 (Adrian and Brunnermeier, 2011; Archarya et al., 2010).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Financial Stability Forum (2009) and U.S.
 Treasury (2009) 
\series default
recommonding that both the FASB and IASB re-evaluate fair value accounting,
 accounting for loan losses, and hedge accounting, among other issues.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Gao and Jiang (2014) argues that reporting discretion can potentially reduce
 bank run.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A large literature examines accounting discretion in banking (Beatty and
 Liao, 2014; Ryan, 2011).
 The literature provides evidence that banks use accounting discretion to
 signal strength and to manage earnigs.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

