\begin_layout Subsection
Bank transparency and regulatory forbearance 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
See Bushman (2015) EPR section 6.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
regulators may practice forbearance by choosing not to intervene and close
 banks that they know to be unsound.
 The literature posits a number of reasons that regulators may practice
 forbearance.
 These include political pressure (Mishkin 2000; Brown and Dinç 2005), loss
 of reputation (Boot and Thakor 1993; Mishkin 2000), or concerns that intervenin
g in one bank can negatively impact the overall financial sector (Brown
 and Dinç 2011; Morrison and White 2013).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Systemic Risk
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Following the recent financial crisis there has been considerable interest
 in modeling and measuring systemic risk.
 There is no agreed upon approach to this measurement (e.g., Bisias et al.,
 2012; Hansen, 2014).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One important stream of literature exploits the high frequency observability
 of banks’ equity prices to extract measures of systemic risk.
 Some papers in this stream use contingent claims analysis (e.g., Gray et
 al.
 2008 and Gray and Jobst, 2009), while others focus on codependence in the
 tails of equity returns using reduced form approaches (Acharya et al., 2010,
 Adrian and Brunnermeier, 2011).
\end_layout

